  <para id="import-auto-id2003308">To construct a nonmechanical water meter, a 0.500-T magnetic field is placed across the supply water pipe to a home and the Hall voltage is recorded. (a) Find the flow rate in liters per second through a 3.00-cm-diameter pipe if the Hall voltage is 60.0 mV. (b) What would the Hall voltage be for the same flow rate through a 10.0-cm-diameter pipe with the same field applied?</para>
</problem></exercise><exercise id="fs-id2077062" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1688484">  <para id="eip-id1168951442441"><title>Integrated Concepts</title></para>  <para id="import-auto-id2760031">(a) Using the values given for an MHD drive in <link target-id="fs-id1993346"/>, and assuming the force is uniformly applied to the fluid, calculate the pressure created in <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mtext>N/m</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mtext>.</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> (b) Is this a significant fraction of an atmosphere?</para></problem>
